1
00:00:02,528 --> 00:00:19,207
Foundation Course 2, Talk 10 The Four Paths and the Four Fruits Another way of looking at the whole process of mental purification is to see it as a release from chains or fetters that tie us to this form of existence.

2
00:00:20,449 --> 00:00:22,812
The Buddha enumerated ten such fetters.

3
00:00:23,812 --> 00:00:29,059
The interesting thing is that in this categorization they are linked with the Progressive Insight.

4
00:00:29,765 --> 00:00:35,493
This progress itself is enumerated as the four paths each having a particular insight or fruit.

5
00:00:36,976 --> 00:00:41,084
When Buddhism talks of the middle path, this is what he meant at the highest level.

6
00:00:42,164 --> 00:00:56,008
Generally, the middle path is understood as the path of moderation in all things, but it can also mean the apex of a triangle which rises above and beyond the two lower paths of sensual indulgence and self-mortification.

7
00:00:56,460 --> 00:01:00,628
Here we shall see how this middle path develops into final liberation.

8
00:01:03,392 --> 00:01:08,719
The first three of these fetters are dissolved, rooted out, with the first insight into Nibbana.

9
00:01:10,003 --> 00:01:16,612
They are wrong view of self, skeptical doubt, and adherence to wrong rites and rituals.

10
00:01:18,718 --> 00:01:26,191
Wrong view of self is believing that the ego, the personality and the body constitute an integral person or substantial soul or self.

11
00:01:27,072 --> 00:01:30,578
It is when we believe the five khanda to be what we really are.

12
00:01:31,581 --> 00:01:42,819
That is why in the meditation practice we try to become more and more aware of the transient, changing, insubstantial nature of the human, this being I call me, this being I call myself or

13
00:01:45,195 --> 00:01:58,897
Therefore, it is not surprising that when a meditator intuits Nibbana, the one thing she comes to know is that whatever the five Kanda are, the body, the sensations, the perception, the volitional conditionings and consciousness itself, it isn't her.

14
00:02:00,058 --> 00:02:06,528
The Nibbanic experience can then be said to be a moment when we discover our true identities, what we really are.

15
00:02:07,623 --> 00:02:17,373
Discovering and realizing ourselves that the third noble truth, the end of suffering, is true, obviously also brings to an end all the skeptical doubt.

16
00:02:18,735 --> 00:02:27,405
Until that moment, we have put confidence in the Buddha's teachings, and we've practiced the meditation and tried to shape our lives around the Noble Eightfold Path.

17
00:02:28,366 --> 00:02:32,871
But until this moment of insight, we cannot know for sure whether it's all true or not.

18
00:02:33,491 --> 00:02:39,177
This not knowing causes fear to arise, and it expresses itself within us as sceptical doubt.

19
00:02:40,300 --> 00:02:41,080
Is it just a trick?

20
00:02:41,600 --> 00:02:44,283
Perhaps the Buddha thought he was enlightened, but maybe he wasn't.

21
00:02:45,025 --> 00:02:46,346
Did the Buddha really know?

22
00:02:47,647 --> 00:02:50,730
This Eightfold Path makes sense, but I don't think it's the whole story.

23
00:02:51,391 --> 00:02:51,731
And so on.

24
00:02:52,832 --> 00:02:56,056
Some people are wracked by these sorts of doubts.

25
00:02:57,015 --> 00:03:08,014
Up until the moment of breakthrough, such people can overcome doubt by raising confidence, by putting trust in the path, at least until the real experiential proof to the opposite arises.

26
00:03:09,997 --> 00:03:14,966
With insight, this sort of confidence, this faith becomes unshakable, for now the person knows.

27
00:03:16,027 --> 00:03:23,580
With this insight, not only is sceptical doubt in the Buddha's path rooted out, but the path leading to total liberation is opened up.

28
00:03:24,168 --> 00:03:35,062
Such a person who enters the Noble Path is called a Sottapanna, which means one who has entered the stream, the stream that will carry them inevitably to total liberation.

29
00:03:36,584 --> 00:03:45,675
Up until this moment also, a meditator may believe that there are other ways of overcoming suffering, such as appealing to a god or performing some magic ceremony or ritual.

30
00:03:46,917 --> 00:03:51,643
It's nice to think that the slate can be wiped clean by special pleading or an act of sacrifice.

31
00:03:52,298 --> 00:04:01,526
So it is, people will make offerings or undergo self-inflicted punishment, believing that this will wipe out the karmic debt.

32
00:04:02,788 --> 00:04:10,415
In Buddha's time, for instance, some ascetics believed that by standing in the river for hours on end, the passing water cleansed the body and the mind.

33
00:04:11,717 --> 00:04:13,679
Insight dispels such wrong views.

34
00:04:14,580 --> 00:04:22,288
The streamentant, the Sotapanna, knows it is only through personal self-endeavor that the mind will be purified and the noble paths won.

35
00:04:22,740 --> 00:04:29,293
Only by accepting the law of karma, only by cleaning up one's own karmic stream, can further insights be made.

36
00:04:30,497 --> 00:04:36,088
It's a bit like a hiker who is lost in a forest, and suddenly in the clearing perceives the mountaintop he's aiming for.

37
00:04:36,810 --> 00:04:38,353
Now he knows the direction.

38
00:04:41,016 --> 00:04:48,709
Because the stream entrant knows the direction, there is no chance such a person will find themselves in circumstances where training cannot continue.

39
00:04:49,610 --> 00:05:05,454
In terms of being born again after death, not something, by the way, that is necessary to believe to benefit from the meditation, such a person need only go through the process of birth and death at the most seven times, and the worst place he can be born into is here, as a human.

40
00:05:07,038 --> 00:05:09,201
Being a human, by the way, was recommended by the Buddha.

41
00:05:09,721 --> 00:05:15,492
He said it was the best place to train, for here a being can confront suffering more easily and discover the way out.

42
00:05:17,357 --> 00:05:21,084
The importance of such people who attain this insight cannot be stressed too much.

43
00:05:22,226 --> 00:05:24,512
They form the backbone of the Buddhist community.

44
00:05:25,132 --> 00:05:30,244
Their firm, unwavering faith helps others to keep going when the going gets rough.

45
00:05:31,692 --> 00:05:33,497
Their own efforts are an inspiration.

46
00:05:34,480 --> 00:05:44,672
Without this continual renewal within the Buddhist community, there is a great danger of a loss of faith and the growth of superstitious beliefs, such as turning the Buddha into a god who can save us.

47
00:05:46,036 --> 00:05:52,502
In the East, it is generally believed that in these so-called corrupt times, people cannot achieve insight.

48
00:05:52,764 --> 00:06:02,233
But one of the greatest scholars in Burma, Lady Sayadaw, said that such views were a danger to the Dharma and urged people to make great effort to attain at least the first path.

49
00:06:05,057 --> 00:06:09,802
When the next noble path and fruit are attained, the next two fetters are only attenuated.

50
00:06:10,302 --> 00:06:13,646
Their grip is loosened, but the person is not free of them.

51
00:06:14,064 --> 00:06:16,547
These two are ill-will and sensual desire.

52
00:06:18,028 --> 00:06:24,175
Such a person is called a sakadagami, or one who needs to be born only once again.

53
00:06:24,896 --> 00:06:32,803
So we see that attaining the paths not only brings us closer to liberation, but also manifests as a change in personality.

54
00:06:33,884 --> 00:06:39,329
At this level, the grip, the obsession with sensual pleasure is greatly diminished.

55
00:06:40,036 --> 00:06:52,853
However, it is not until the third path, the anagami, that the one who will not return, the non-returner, that the shackles, the fetters of sensual desire and ill-will are finally rooted out.

56
00:06:55,317 --> 00:07:04,608
Finally, there is the last stage, the arahat, one who has killed all enemies, meaning, of course, the roots of unwholesomeness, greed, hatred and delusion.

57
00:07:06,630 --> 00:07:14,319
In that absolute liberation, all the fetters that chain us to the wheel of dependent origination, the wheel of becoming, are finally rooted out for good.

58
00:07:15,540 --> 00:07:24,428
The final five fetters are the craving for the realm of forms and the formless realms, conceit, restlessness and ignorance.

59
00:07:26,071 --> 00:07:35,439
The realms refer to states of mind achievable through concentration meditation and also to realms of existence, where a being proficient in these skills can be born.

60
00:07:35,807 --> 00:07:41,158
But like all places in this phenomenal universe, they suffer from the wrath of transiency and don't last.

61
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:51,877
Losing desire for such blissful states of mind means that the Arahant has no wish at all to stay in this world of change, samsara, this ever going on and on.

62
00:07:53,079 --> 00:07:55,182
All desire for sense pleasure is gone.

63
00:07:56,310 --> 00:08:08,353
Although an arahat may be reborn in a high plane upon death until all karma is finally run out, once this has passed, he passes into parinibbana, total nibbana, as have all the Buddhas.

64
00:08:09,475 --> 00:08:10,937
This state is never described.

65
00:08:11,278 --> 00:08:13,442
The Buddha said it was indescribable.

66
00:08:15,886 --> 00:08:21,153
It is interesting to note that conceit and restlessness stay up to the bitter end.

67
00:08:21,834 --> 00:08:24,678
Conceit, of course, arises out of wrong view of self.

68
00:08:25,459 --> 00:08:28,384
So all the other path-winners do not do away with ego.

69
00:08:29,706 --> 00:08:32,991
Even though they may know who they truly are, there is still delusion.

70
00:08:33,511 --> 00:08:36,777
There is still attachment to the five khanda, this body and mind.

71
00:08:37,778 --> 00:08:43,226
So long as there is even an iota of attachment, so long will there be wrong view of self.

72
00:08:44,287 --> 00:08:46,708
This, of course, is ignorance, the last fetter.

73
00:08:47,789 --> 00:08:54,756
Not until the heart is totally purified will we ever stop creating unwholesome karma, no matter how insignificant it may be.

74
00:08:55,456 --> 00:08:58,701
This unwholesome karma always causes mental disturbance.

75
00:08:59,782 --> 00:09:03,004
This is the restlessness that final liberation does away with.

76
00:09:04,046 --> 00:09:08,370
So that's why those on the first three paths are called seka, meaning trainees.

77
00:09:09,490 --> 00:09:10,951
Work still has to be done.

78
00:09:11,489 --> 00:09:15,375
but the arahant is called aseka, no more training is necessary.

79
00:09:16,596 --> 00:09:24,827
That final liberation also brings with it the consummate knowledge of the svakata Buddha, the enlightened being who was a follower of the Buddha.

80
00:09:24,847 --> 00:09:26,571
He becomes one who knows.

81
00:09:28,092 --> 00:09:35,082
All ignorance as to the true nature of samsara, this phenomenal universe, this universe of becoming, is dispelled.

82
00:09:35,485 --> 00:09:44,835
It's important here to note that the Buddha didn't call himself a master, but a guide, one who leads people to the higher understandings and attainments.

83
00:09:45,534 --> 00:09:47,817
He didn't want disciples to remain disciples.

84
00:09:48,238 --> 00:09:54,804
He wanted them to become masters, to master the path, and become equal to him in the knowledge of the Enlightenment.

85
00:09:56,225 --> 00:10:04,934
That is why followers who achieve the total Enlightenment, the highest path of the Arhat, are known as Svakata Buddhas, Buddhas who are disciples of a Buddha.

86
00:10:07,565 --> 00:10:13,591
The joy of such attainment, of such liberation, is beautifully recorded in the words of Kisagatami.

87
00:10:14,493 --> 00:10:20,019
She was a woman who had turned up at the Buddha's monastery with her dead child and had asked him to bring the child back to life.

88
00:10:20,820 --> 00:10:31,110
She had gone from door to door looking for a mustard seed from a house where there had been no death, believing that if she found one, the Buddha would be able to perform a magic ritual and resurrect her child.

89
00:10:31,672 --> 00:10:36,136
Of course, she never found one and came back much enlightened by her experience.

90
00:10:36,352 --> 00:10:40,259
for it had taught her that death is inescapable and part and parcel of this universe.

91
00:10:41,321 --> 00:10:44,566
She joined the order and later achieved arahatship.

92
00:10:45,386 --> 00:10:46,929
These are her victory verses.

93
00:10:48,611 --> 00:10:49,113
Hear me.

94
00:10:50,095 --> 00:10:55,283
I have travelled upon the noble eightfold path that leads to that state of sheer happiness.

95
00:10:56,384 --> 00:11:01,753
It is nibbana itself I have realised, and I have gazed into the mirror of the holy norm.

96
00:11:02,357 --> 00:11:05,764
Yes, I, even I, am healed of my suffering.

97
00:11:06,304 --> 00:11:07,687
My burden is laid down.

98
00:11:08,227 --> 00:11:09,330
My task is done.

99
00:11:09,890 --> 00:11:12,174
My heart is set totally free.

100
00:11:13,116 --> 00:11:15,981
This is I, Sister Gautami, who have said this.

101
00:11:18,365 --> 00:11:23,235
The Buddha himself, of course, stands as the greatest of all in this dispensation.

102
00:11:23,467 --> 00:11:32,422
What gives him that special stature is that he is the sammasambuddho, the fully self-enlightened one, and that he is the one who is the teacher of humankind.

103
00:11:33,582 --> 00:11:44,440
Whatever field we look at, be it religious or scientific, artistic, historical or social, the ones remembered are the ones who started things, accomplished something for the first time, discovered something.

104
00:11:45,741 --> 00:11:50,269
The spiritual quest is often compared to mountain climbing, and here it works very well.

105
00:11:51,312 --> 00:11:59,519
So many attempts were made to climb Everest, but not until Sherpa Tensing and Edmund Hillary actually made it did people know it was really possible.

106
00:12:00,961 --> 00:12:09,607
After their conquest, everything became that much easier because now climbers knew it could be done, and from that knowledge took confidence and courage.

107
00:12:10,708 --> 00:12:11,429
So with the Buddha.

108
00:12:12,451 --> 00:12:19,277
His life itself and the teachings are a monument and a description of that most difficult of peaks to be conquered.

109
00:12:19,914 --> 00:12:27,442
And just as Tensing and Hillary are regarded with special honour and affection in mountaineering circles, so the Buddha is venerated by his followers.

110
00:12:29,865 --> 00:12:33,809
The special qualities of a Buddha are chanted most times that Buddhists come together.

111
00:12:34,630 --> 00:12:36,052
It starts with a salutation.

112
00:12:36,832 --> 00:12:47,104
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Hail to the Blessed One, the Arahat, the fully self-enlightened one.

113
00:12:48,096 --> 00:12:51,039
Then, in the Theravada tradition, the qualities are chanted.

114
00:12:52,422 --> 00:13:00,711
They are, first of all, that he is an Arahant, one who has destroyed all the enemies of the spiritual path and uprooted Greek hatred and delusion.

115
00:13:02,274 --> 00:13:07,639
Because of this, he has broken the spokes of the wheel of dependent origination, the wheel of becoming, and gone beyond.

116
00:13:08,081 --> 00:13:10,222
Therefore, he is worthy of homage.

117
00:13:11,299 --> 00:13:21,504
The second is the fact that he is fully self-enlightened, fully in that he knows what suffering is, what the cause is, what the end of all suffering is, and the path leading to that end.

118
00:13:22,346 --> 00:13:23,548
This is what a Buddha knows.

119
00:13:25,594 --> 00:13:29,442
What is more, he achieved this by his own endeavour and without a guide.

120
00:13:30,975 --> 00:13:41,193
Having achieved the enlightenment, the third characteristic is that he became endowed with clear knowledge, clear vision and virtuous conduct, perfect moral behavior.

121
00:13:42,475 --> 00:13:48,346
There was no separation in him between what he said and how he behaved, what he said he did.

122
00:13:49,849 --> 00:13:56,139
His behavior came out of wisdom and its special sign was a devotion to wakefulness, bright awareness.

123
00:13:57,216 --> 00:14:03,325
Indeed, there is a discourse when Ananda, his attendant, enumerates the wonderful and marvellous qualities of the Buddha.

124
00:14:04,166 --> 00:14:12,216
But there is one thing he leaves out, and this, the Buddha says, is what is also remarkable about a Buddha, his continuous unbroken awareness.

125
00:14:14,418 --> 00:14:22,649
All you have said is true, but remember this also, Ananda, that this is also a wondrous and marvellous quality of the perfected one.

126
00:14:23,052 --> 00:14:28,360
An accomplished one is aware of feelings, be they pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

127
00:14:28,881 --> 00:14:32,347
He is aware of them as they arise and as they pass away.

128
00:14:33,690 --> 00:14:39,799
And so he says that he is equally aware of all the other five khandhas, the perceptions, the volitional conditionings and consciousness.

129
00:14:42,485 --> 00:14:46,191
Having achieved the Buddhahood, the journeying itself was accomplished.

130
00:14:47,081 --> 00:14:53,327
He had made a commitment to the Buddha of the last dispensation, Dipankara, at whose feet he determined to become a Buddha.

131
00:14:54,389 --> 00:15:01,437
Life after life he trained to achieve the necessary perfections, so that eventually he could discover the path without a guide.

132
00:15:02,577 --> 00:15:11,807
So he is called Sugato, often translated unhappily as well-gone, but it means to have completed the journey to enlightenment with distinction.

133
00:15:13,340 --> 00:15:24,058
The Buddha actually refers to himself in the scriptures as the Tathagata, one who has gone or travelled thus, meaning this journey to enlightenment.

134
00:15:24,078 --> 00:15:28,046
This journey revealed to him the nature of the world we live in and of all the realms.

135
00:15:28,866 --> 00:15:33,475
So it is that his fourth quality is that of a knower of the worlds.

136
00:15:35,480 --> 00:15:44,467
Having achieved his Buddhahood, he decided to teach, and so he is called incomparable trainer or leader of human beings who need to be tamed or trained.

137
00:15:45,629 --> 00:15:51,673
He is the teacher of gods and humankind, and this he did out of compassion to alleviate their suffering.

138
00:15:52,855 --> 00:15:57,119
In other scriptures he is called the Mahakaruniko, the great compassionate one.

139
00:15:58,139 --> 00:16:03,445
And so it is that he is enlightened, the awakener of humankind, and blessed.

140
00:16:03,761 --> 00:16:07,586
and deserving respect and veneration on account of these consummate qualities.

141
00:16:09,229 --> 00:16:14,394
So in the Theravada tradition, these are the nine qualities enumerated which belong to a Buddha.

142
00:16:15,716 --> 00:16:16,857
Thus is the Blessed One.

143
00:16:17,599 --> 00:16:31,254
He is an arahat, fully self-enlightened, endowed with clear knowledge and virtuous conduct, his journey well accomplished, knower of the world, incomparable charioteer of people to be trained.

144
00:16:31,657 --> 00:16:38,768
teacher of devas, those who dwell in the higher realms, here often translated as gods, and humankind.

145
00:16:39,850 --> 00:16:41,452
Enlightened and blessed.

146
00:16:44,317 --> 00:16:46,801
This brings us to devotion in Buddhism.

147
00:16:48,344 --> 00:16:52,811
Anyone entering a Buddhist shrine would immediately think that people are praying to a god and so on.

148
00:16:53,491 --> 00:16:57,158
The external trappings are the same in as many another religion.

149
00:16:57,408 --> 00:17:04,397
the statue of the founder, the special veneration he is held in, the candles, the incense, the flowers, the bells and smells, and so on.

150
00:17:05,779 --> 00:17:08,724
However, in Buddhism, devotion takes on a different meaning.

151
00:17:09,566 --> 00:17:24,428
Rather than an outpouring of emotions, it is a conscious, determined effort to bring to mind the qualities of the Buddha, Dharma, Sangha, the three refuges, the triple gem, and to ponder their meanings, for it is to these qualities that one devotes oneself.

152
00:17:24,880 --> 00:17:33,769
That's devotion, to take on, to train oneself, to devote oneself to achieving the qualities of an Arhat, the Svakata Buddha.

153
00:17:35,530 --> 00:17:46,542
No doubt, when a Buddhist or a meditator considers the life and work of the Buddha and what they have gained from the teaching and the practice, great feelings of thankfulness and praise arise.

154
00:17:47,544 --> 00:17:51,748
This is the heart's natural response to the generosity of the Buddhas and the saints.

155
00:17:52,707 --> 00:17:59,753
One can feel such gratitude for many another person, mother and father, friends who have helped us in need, public servants and so on.

156
00:18:00,974 --> 00:18:11,585
Although when these feelings arise there is great warmth and lightness in the heart, they would be of little use if they were not also seen as motivators to take up the path more seriously.

157
00:18:12,925 --> 00:18:19,051
What's the point of going around telling everyone what a lovely and wonderful doctor you've got when you never take a prescribed medicine?

158
00:18:20,737 --> 00:18:28,527
Such emotions that arise of praise and gratitude can all be used by devotees to urge themselves along the path.

159
00:18:30,028 --> 00:18:43,605
If this is not so, if the Buddhist believes that performing a few ceremonies such as lighting candles and bowings and feeling good about it is all that is required for liberation, they are simply strengthening the fetter of adherence to wrong rites and rituals.

160
00:18:44,480 --> 00:18:51,190
It becomes right ritual and ceremony when it helps to further our training, to further a person along the path.

161
00:18:52,432 --> 00:18:59,301
So when a Buddhist bows to a Buddha statue called the Buddha Rupa, he is saying something like, Thank you for your teaching.

162
00:18:59,663 --> 00:19:01,404
I shall devote myself to the path.

163
00:19:01,945 --> 00:19:03,608
I submit myself to your wisdom.

164
00:19:04,410 --> 00:19:07,855
I have faith that it will lead me to my liberation.

165
00:19:09,049 --> 00:19:15,861
When a Buddhist lights the candles, she may call to mind the enlightenment and determine to achieve insight into one of the paths.

166
00:19:16,902 --> 00:19:25,375
When she lights incense, she may call to mind the law of karma, that good deeds pervade the universe just as the scent of incense pervades the air.

167
00:19:26,757 --> 00:19:33,027
When she sets out the flowers, she may remind herself of the essential characteristic of the universe, transiency change.

168
00:19:34,368 --> 00:19:36,271
Even the most beautiful bloom must fade.

169
00:19:37,585 --> 00:19:41,891
Whatever a devotee does in the shrine room has this symbolic quality about it.

170
00:19:43,093 --> 00:19:44,875
They are all aids to reflection.

171
00:19:45,855 --> 00:19:54,007
Even the chanting is simply recalling to mind the teachings of the Buddha, constantly developing right understanding of the Noble Eightfold Path.

172
00:19:56,590 --> 00:20:00,336
This same devotion is also developed towards the Dharma, the second refuge.

173
00:20:01,336 --> 00:20:03,980
The Dharma is said to be thoroughly explained by the Buddha.

174
00:20:05,023 --> 00:20:11,192
When one realizes the Dharma within oneself, this is the same as gaining the four paths of insight and their fruit.

175
00:20:12,074 --> 00:20:14,497
The results of such insights are immediate.

176
00:20:15,659 --> 00:20:19,083
This is why Buddhism talks of the eightfold kinds of noble persons.

177
00:20:20,224 --> 00:20:27,213
Each individual can achieve the four paths of insight and so gain the four fruits of these achievements.

178
00:20:27,233 --> 00:20:29,396
The Dharma is said to invite investigation.

179
00:20:29,798 --> 00:20:31,420
It's not just to be believed.

180
00:20:32,632 --> 00:20:33,773
It leads to nibbana.

181
00:20:34,314 --> 00:20:36,076
Nibbana is the end of training.

182
00:20:36,396 --> 00:20:37,778
It's the goal, the highest good.

183
00:20:38,780 --> 00:20:43,027
And finally, the Dharma has to be understood by each person individually.

184
00:20:43,567 --> 00:20:46,151
No one else can understand or experience this for us.

185
00:20:46,612 --> 00:20:47,692
We have to do the work.

186
00:20:49,115 --> 00:20:53,801
Again, this is all part of Buddhist devotion, to devote oneself to realizing the Dharma.

187
00:20:55,984 --> 00:20:57,406
Devotion to the Sangha

188
00:20:57,573 --> 00:21:04,960
which here means the eight kinds of persons, those who have entered the paths, is to recognize their unique position in the Buddhist community.

189
00:21:06,260 --> 00:21:10,065
Their conduct is said to be good, upright, wise and dutiful.

190
00:21:10,885 --> 00:21:20,015
For this reason, they are worthy of offerings, of hospitality, of gifts and reverential salutation, for they constitute an incomparable field of merit for the world.

191
00:21:20,976 --> 00:21:26,601
In other words, if you praise someone's way of life and livelihood, you want to support them.

192
00:21:27,204 --> 00:21:30,647
Remember, such people can be both monastics and lay people.

193
00:21:31,469 --> 00:21:38,996
However, monks and nuns are more visibly trying to lead the holy life, and so are obviously treated with greater respect.

194
00:21:39,817 --> 00:21:42,439
And to some, many show great devotion.

195
00:21:44,882 --> 00:21:47,844
The manner of showing devotion differs according to the culture.

196
00:21:48,724 --> 00:21:53,769
In Japan, monks and lay people will hold their hands together as if in a form of prayer and bow.

197
00:21:54,509 --> 00:21:57,792
They will bow this way to statues of the Buddha, the Buddha Rupa.

198
00:21:58,933 --> 00:22:04,819
In our tradition, there is a full body bow which is done towards the Buddha Rupa or to monks on occasion.

199
00:22:06,041 --> 00:22:11,347
Five parts of the body are to touch the ground, the two knees, the two hands and the forehead.

200
00:22:12,528 --> 00:22:19,195
To us in the West, it seems a little over the top, but a great deal of study has been done in the West on the meaning of body postures.

201
00:22:20,157 --> 00:22:24,162
It is through our body and facial expressions that we also communicate what we mean.

202
00:22:25,356 --> 00:22:29,343
We stand in a different way when we're with a friend from when we're with the boss.

203
00:22:29,762 --> 00:22:37,173
With the boss, we tend to stand a little more alertly, some say respectfully, and if we are taller, we tend to bend just a little to show deference.

204
00:22:38,674 --> 00:22:40,778
Bowing can teach us a lot about ourselves.

205
00:22:41,398 --> 00:22:45,625
I recommend you try, and just notice how the mind reacts with all its opinions.

206
00:22:46,926 --> 00:22:52,815
I certainly butted against it when I first came to Buddhism, but now I find it a very meaningful practice.

207
00:22:55,073 --> 00:23:00,819
So we've covered here the four different paths of sainthood, the meaning of the refuges, and of devotion.

208
00:23:02,201 --> 00:23:10,971
This is also the last talk, and therefore I think it right and proper to end with the victory verse of the Buddha himself, which he is said to have uttered upon enlightenment.

209
00:23:11,772 --> 00:23:16,157
They are recorded in the Dhammapada.

210
00:23:16,178 --> 00:23:19,781
I, who have been seeking the house-builder of this body...

211
00:23:19,963 --> 00:23:27,132
failing to achieve enlightenment by which I could discover him, have wandered through innumerable births in Samsara.

212
00:23:28,354 --> 00:23:32,178
To be born again and again is indeed suffering.

213
00:23:33,298 --> 00:23:36,343
But now, O householder, you have been caught.

214
00:23:37,103 --> 00:23:39,086
You shall build no more houses for me.

215
00:23:39,145 --> 00:23:44,531
All your rafters have been broken asunder, your gable-top destroyed.

216
00:23:45,673 --> 00:23:49,076
My mind has attained the unconditioned.

217
00:23:49,174 --> 00:23:51,795
The end of suffering has been achieved.

218
00:23:55,300 --> 00:23:58,324
Well, I hope this talk has been interesting and helpful.

